{"title":"DELL: Generating Reactions and Explanations for LLM-Based Misinformation Detection","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Misinformation detectors benefit from social-context signals (user comments and propagation), but real comments are scarce, hard to collect in real time, and may be incomplete; LLMs used directly for veracity judgments also suffer from hallucinations and factuality issues.","method":"DELL uses LLMs to synthesize diverse community reactions and build user–news interaction networks. It samples user profiles across seven demographic/political attributes and iteratively prompts the LLM to (i) comment on the news, (ii) reply to a comment, or (iii) select a comment chain to engage, controlling graph shape via α (comment-on-news probability), β (height/width balance), and k (candidate set size). The generated networks statistically resemble real ones (e.g., Pheme) and, when used as graph inputs, improve detection performance and robustness to comment sparsity."},{"problem":"Assessing news veracity requires latent contexts (sentiment, framing, propaganda tactics, external knowledge, inter-comment relations) that are not explicit in the article text and are underutilized by standard classifiers.","method":"DELL defines six explainable proxy tasks executed by LLMs: sentiment (select 3 of 6 basic emotions + rationale), framing (select 5 of 14 frames + rationale), propaganda tactics (select 5 of 19 + rationale), knowledge retrieval (identify entities and prepend Wikipedia passages), stance between linked nodes, and response characterization. For each expert, DELL encodes the original text and the LLM-generated explanation with DeBERTa, concatenates their embeddings to initialize node features, and applies a GIN-based GNN over the user–news graph. Task-specific experts specialize in different aspects, and even a single expert notably boosts macro-F1 over strong baselines."},{"problem":"Combining multiple specialized predictors often treats experts equally and ignores confidence, hurting both accuracy and calibration when experts vary in reliability per instance.","method":"DELL introduces an LLM-based expert ensemble: provide the LLM with the news, expert descriptions, and each expert’s predicted labels; in Confidence mode, also verbalize experts’ confidence from the GNN classifier (softmax max prob for binary, absolute logits for multi-label); in Selective mode, first ask the LLM which experts to activate, then aggregate with confidence. This selective, confidence-aware merging improves macro-F1 on most datasets and yields better-calibrated detectors (e.g., ECE ≈ 0.2357, up to 19.1% improvement vs. baselines)."}]}
